lly threatened the core of Christian belief. Gilman also trains his critical eye on the works of Jonson, Donne, Pepys, and Defoe, which, he posits, can be more fully understood when put into the context of this century-long project to “write out” the plague. Ultimately, Plague Writing in Early Modern England is more than a compendium of artifacts of a bygone era; it holds up a distant mirror to reflect our own condition in the age of AIDS, super viruses, multidrug resistant tuberculosis, and the hovering threat of a global flu pandemic.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aDiseases and literaturezGreat BritainxHistoryy17th century. 0aDiseases in literature. 0aEnglish literatureyEarly modern, 1500-1700xHistory and criticism. 0aEpidemics in literature. 0aEpidemicszEnglandxHistoryy17th century. 0aLiterature and societyzGreat BritainxHistoryy17th century. 0aPlague in literature. 0aPlaguexPolitical aspects. 0aPlaguexReligious aspects. 0aPlaguezEnglandxHistoryy17th century. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh  ahistory of medicine, 17th century, epidemics, bubonic plague, london, urban centers, sermons, preachers, religion, faith, natural disasters, medical tracts, pious exhortations, satirical pamphlets, political commentary, divine justice, christian belief, pepys, defoe, early modern england, super viruses, global pandemic, great britain, regime change, ben jonson, john donne.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311063538640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226294117423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226294117/original  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles